metadata.name: Crop Circles #19
metadata.description:
A crop circle is a pattern created by flattening a crop. The number of reports of crop circles has substantially increased since the 1970s. There has been scant scientific study of them. Circles are not distributed randomly across the landscape but appear near roads, areas of medium to dense population and cultural heritage monuments.

They are made by aliens.

Heightmap drawn with p5.js lines.

* Variations:

- Inner design
- Outer design
- Crop color
- Field cuts
- Rotation
- Zoom

metadata.name: Dancing bubbles #76
metadata.description:
Dancing bubbles is a mesmerizing form of visual art that captures bubble beauty and fluidity. It involves creating intricate and vibrant designs using bubbles as generative art.
The process begins by mixing a special solution that creates long-lasting and colorful bubbles. I carefully blew these bubbles onto the canvas and let them float and move freely. As the bubbles interact with each other, they create stunning patterns and shapes.
I manipulated the direction, colors, and movement of the bubbles using live patterns and directed them across the canvas to create dynamic compositions.
When the bubbles merge, they leave a vibrant trail, creating unique textures and patterns on the canvas. The result is a captivating work of art that comes alive with its own fluidity and movement.
Dancing bubbles are visually appealing, but they also evoke joy and playfulness. It captures the fleeting nature of bubbles and reminds us to appreciate beautiful moments that are fleeting yet magical.
This art form can be enjoyed in various settings, including galleries, exhibitions, or even live performances in aquariums decorated with colored lights. It's a delightful experience for me and viewers alike, as we watch the creation of ephemeral catches of bubbles that dance before our eyes.

Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Arts & Poetry - Vol. 2
metadata.description:
In this second volume, we break new ground – adding GIF and video functionality with poems and visual art from 20 of Web3's rising stars, including Jono, Futuradora, Mark Fitzpatrick, H.C. Holter, and many more.

Featuring voices from around the world – Africa, the Americas, Europe and Australia – this is a unique literary NFT which engages the eyes and ears, the heart and mind. 

Because this is an interactive token, I recommend activating “advanced mode” in the Objkt interface to enjoy all its functionality – and to turn up your volume, since one of the pieces enhances the words and visuals of the poet’s work with sound.

A key feature of this piece that I wanted to highlight is that every contributor receives an equal share of all sales – 1/20th of the initial sale price and the secondary royalties. This is a much more equitable approach than that of traditional journals – and an example of the way that NFTs can improve collaborative, cooperative approaches to valuing the work of poets, artists, and other creatives!

It is also a cross-chain project – there will be copies on the Polygon blockchain through the “Readl” platform, which (like Objkt) features a simple method for organically splitting creator payments across 20 wallets.

Future volumes will be released simultaneously (and at similar price points) on Polygon and Tezos – and we will look to bring on support for Solana, Cardano, and Ethereum in the future, in order to promote the spread of poetry and art in a way that allows collectors to connect with art regardless of which blockchain they prefer.

metadata.name: rosarium #185
metadata.description:
"rosarium" is part of the live minting experience at Non Fungible Conference Lisbon, June 7-8, 2023.

Each iteration of rosarium is an arrangement of several unique species of ethereal, alien, and yet familiar flowers.

This piece uses progressive volumetric rendering to produce photorealistic images. It may take several seconds to produce a recognizable image, and several minutes to produce a high-quality render with no visible noise.

Created with webgl and clojurescript.

Controls:

Click on the canvas to open a menu in the top right corner. In this menu you will see controls to capture a screenshot, adjust resolution, and adjust the camera, along with several other controls.

When the "optimized render" option is checked, the page will compute an acceleration structure before rendering to allow the piece to converge much faster. With this option checked, the piece may need to process for up to a minute before rendering begins, but subsequently the rendering will proceed much more quickly than normal. This can be used to generate high-quality captures more quickly than when the option is not checked.

When the "filtering" option is checked, a noise filter will be applied to the result of the render, reducing the appearance of noise.

The "logic multiple" slider can be used to multiply the amount of rendering work done each frame. Increasing this number may allow the piece to render more quickly, but may also make the page laggy. It is not recommended to increase this number unless you have a powerful GPU.
